<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36048f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36048f">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36048f"> 48(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Broken backed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But that those who remained pagan adhered to the worship of Thor, then the religion of Norway, can only be inferred from the few events, which are recorded in our Annals. For instance, we know that the Scandinavians sometimes sacrificed their prisoners to Thor or Odin, by &ldquo;crushing the spine&rdquo; (or &ldquo;<mark>breaking the back on a stone</mark>&rdquo;), or by plunging the victim head foremost in water, and auguring from the sacrifice future victory. <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD5" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD5"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 126</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
